# Source editing rules

These rules apply when editing application source code (services, packages, apps).

## Pre-edit gate

- `direct`: low-risk source edits may start after classification; disclose user-owned checks.
- `assisted`: require `.maestro/work/tasks/<task_id>/task.yaml` for continuity.
- `governed`: require `task-analysis.yaml` and the full applicable gate sequence.
- If `architecture_review.required: true` in `task-analysis.yaml`, do not plan or code until `.maestro/work/tasks/<task_id>/architecture-review.yaml` has decision `approved`.
- In the standard pipeline, do not modify application source before `implementation-plan.yaml` and `service-assignments.yaml` exist.
- In product-component fast-track, `task-analysis.yaml.context_plan` and a lightweight `service-assignments.yaml` are still required; only the full `implementation-plan.yaml` is skipped.
- Cursor's `check-task-analysis.sh` hook enforces the selected execution mode and governed gates.

## Scope enforcement (R-006)

- Generated service coders write only inside `allowed_write_paths` from `.maestro/registry/agents.yaml`.
- Never write outside the assigned service scope; raise `cross_service_request` to Coder Leader instead.
- Cross-cutting coders (`coder-infra`, `coder-database`, `coder-data`) do not touch application source code.

## Code quality (R-005-09)

- Reuse existing helpers from the project before writing new ones (check `.maestro/memory/project/common/generics.md` and `conventions.md`).
- Coder Leader reviews architecture/layer boundaries, dependency direction, reuse, and contract changes BEFORE Dev Verification.

## Tests

- Follow `.maestro/knowledge/test-policy.yaml` per service.
- Do not create test files if `unit_tests_required: false`.
- If tests required, update tests using existing project conventions — do not introduce new test frameworks without approval.

## Anti-guessing

- Do not invent APIs, file paths, or library versions. If unknown, mark `unknown` and ask.
- Verify critical claims (build passes, test passes) with concrete commands before claiming done.
